  "text": "Mothering is also viewed as a social construct with historical and cultural variation. It is broadly conceived as the work that women do in caring for and nurturing children [CITATION_1] ). Ruddick's (1980; classic research framed mothering within this caring and nurturing construct. She used the concept of maternal practice to describe mothering. She argued that mothers are concerned with protecting, preserving, and fostering their children's growth and development. She noted that mothering must be done within acceptable parameters of the social group (1980) because mothers are held accountable for raising their children. Mothers need to solve and negotiate these conflicting demands, and this is not always easy.",
